7.1: Linear Regression¶

Regression algorithms are used when the outcome of interest is a continuous variable.

Linear Regression models the relationship between the dependent and independent variables in a linear way.

The fitted model produces a linear line (or surface for higher dimensional data), which is used

The model tries to minimize the total squared error between the predictions and the actual outcomes. This is often done by using the Least Squares Method.

Simple Linear Regression \begin{align} y^{i} & = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} x^{i} + \epsilon^{i} \\ \end{align}

Multiple Linear Regression \begin{align} y^{i} & = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} x^{i}_{1} + \beta_{2} x^{i}_{2} + ... + \beta_{k} x^{i}_{k} +\epsilon^{i} \\ \end{align}

# Putting all together
#Import all necessary packages
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import sklearn.datasets as data #Scikit-learn can import datasets
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn import metrics

# Load dataset
wine=data.load_wine()

# Convert dataset to dataframes
df2=pd.DataFrame(wine.data, columns=wine.feature_names)

# Add target to the DataFrame
df2['wine_type']=wine.target

# Instantiate the estimator as ensues
reg=LinearRegression()

# Create and select X and Y datasets
x=df2[['proline']] # Must be 2D or Pandas DataFrame
y=df2['alcohol'] #1D or pandas series

# Fit the model with training data
reg.fit(x, y)

# Perform prediction using test dataset
pred=reg.predict(x)

# Compute accuracy using metrics score
acc=metrics.r2_score(y, pred)
print(f"The accuracy is {acc}")

The accuracy is 0.41437548626472054

7.2: Logistic Regression¶

A classification Algorithm

When the output variable is a category of limited number of possibilities, then classification methods will come into play.

Logistic regression is the first supervised learning classification algorithm that we'll learn about.

The linear model used in linear regression is transformed by using the sigmoid function so that the predictions always lie between 0 and 1 (probability)

Binary dependent variables, can be extended to predict outputs with more than 2 variables (multinomial logistic regression)

It is a family of linear models called generalized linear model (GLM)

Simple Logistic Regression

\begin{align} g(z) & =\frac{1}{1 + e^{-z}}\\ \end{align}

Multiple Logistic Regression

\begin{align} P(y=1) & =\frac{1}{1 + e^{-(\beta_{0} + \beta_{1} x_{1} + \beta_{2} x_{2} + ... + \beta_{k} x_{k})}}\\ \end{align}

False Negatives: intended values or objects but estimated or classified or detected as non-intended.

7.3: K-Nearest Neighbors¶

Classifier points based on distance to closest k number of points

Learning is done by similarity, meaning the most similiar points which are closest to the point of interest determine its class (voting)

Not good with high dimensional data. The curse of dimensionality!

Categorical features are usually not good to deal with

Normalizing the data usually will increase accuracy. Otherwise variables with larger values will dominate the distance metric. Use the right normalization methods like

\begin{align} \frac{x-\mu}{\sigma} \ or \ \frac{X-X_{min}}{X_{max}-X_{min}}\\ \end{align}

Very large dataset can be extremely slow. However, algorithms have been developed to optimize the process.

Example: Classify the blackpoint:

7.4: Decision Trees¶

For example, when guessing a country name one starts with questions like:

is it in Northern Hemisphere?
is it in Europe?
is its GDP larger than X amount

Works like a human mind, and is easy to represent and interpret

Is a non-linear model

Graph like structure where nodes represent decisions to split on, and leaves represent the outcome.

The feature to split on is selected based on Information gain or Entropy

The basic principle is to reduce impurity or to increase information gain as much as possible.

Results in lower variance in the branches after splitting, meaning more points from the same class leads to lower entropy values (less impurity).

The first feature to split on is the most import one that results in largest decrease in impurity.

$$Entropy=-\sum_{i=0}^n (p_{i}) log_{2}(p_{i})$$

Information Gain = Entropy Parent - Weighted Average of Entropy CHildren

Goal: Maximize Information Gain

7.5: Random Forest¶

Many decision trees coming together (put together) make up a forest

Is an ensemble learning technique

Ensemble methods use multiple learning algorithms which will yield better predictive performance than the ones constituting the ensemble.

Usually ever 1 or 2 level deep trees are enough for a random forest to perform much better than a single deep decision tree.

A subset of bootstrapped data, and subset of features are used in each tree

sqrt (total # of features) number of features are selected randomly.

The final decision depends on the majority vote

Helps decrease the high variance that results from using a single tree

More robust and generalizable compared to decision trees

The variables that are used by many trees will hint their importance

Bootstrapping is random selection with replacement. The same row and the same columns can be selected multiple times.

7.6: K-Means Clustering¶

K-means clustering

No labels are used - unsupervised learning

The basic principle is to cluster the points to the nearest centroid

There are K number of centroids (mean of the clusters)

The algorithm is very similar to K-means neigbors, however that one is supervised and instance based learning - meaning all the points in training data were used to classify, whereas the K-means only uses the K centroids to cluster the points.

Observations are clustered into k groups, where each observation is assigned to the group with the nearest mean.

Need to decide on K

The created clusters can be used as a feature for other algorithms

Used in market segmentation, image segmentation and more

Not friendly with non-numerical data

Good when groups are distinct and linearly separable

Not good when too much overlapping, too much noise or outliers

The created K-clusters can be used as features for other algorithms

As depicted in the figure below, three centroids/means are provided and the distance of each point to the means is computed and is clustered to the closest centroid.
